# Rename Consistency

Past refactors renamed concepts in this codebase. The dead spelling keeps re-appearing in new agent-authored code because the model's training data still remembers the old name. This is *consistency hygiene*, not a banned-words list — every entry has a concrete migration behind it.

## Active renames

| Old | New | Why |
|---|---|---|
| _(none tracked yet)_ | | |

When you complete a rename, add the row here and a check below. Otherwise the dead form will reappear in the next agent's output.

## Rules

- When introducing a new symbol, route, doc heading, or comment, search the codebase for the data-model name first; do not fall back to the dead UX metaphor or historical brand.
- If a lint/policy check fails on a file you did not author for one of these renames, follow `multi-agent.mdc` rule 5 — flag it but do not "fix" the sibling agent's work.
- When landing a new rename, add a check to the project's policy script (or pre-commit hook) modelled on existing ones before declaring the rename done. Allowlists for legitimate references (vendor names, marketing copy, third-party APIs that still use the old term) live in that script — extend the allowlist there if you have a justified reference, do not edit around the check.

## Why this rule exists

LLMs reach for the most common spelling in their training data, which is usually the *first* name a project used — even if the codebase has since renamed it. Without a mechanical gate, every new agent-authored file slowly reintroduces dead terminology and the rename never finishes.

The rule pairs with `no-competing-versions.mdc`: deletion-of-old + grep-for-old together finish the migration. Either alone is insufficient.

